    <p class="page-label">The Rover</p>
    <h1 class="page-title">Your child builds it. Programs it. Keeps it.</h1>
    <p class="page-sub">The Mission Mars Rover is not a toy — it's a real programmable robot, designed and engineered in Hong Kong by CreatorPort.</p>

    <div class="rover-hero">
      <img src="/rover-pink.png" alt="Mission Mars Rover" />
    </div>

    <h2 class="section-title">What's inside</h2>
    <ul class="spec-list">
      <li><strong>Brain</strong>Arduino-based microcontroller — the same platform used in university engineering labs worldwide</li>
      <li><strong>Movement</strong>Dual DC motors with independent control — drives, turns, reverses, spins</li>
      <li><strong>Gripper</strong>Servo-powered mechanical arm — picks up, lifts, and places objects on the Mars surface</li>
      <li><strong>Drill</strong>Motorized drill attachment — breaks through terrain to prepare the ground for planting</li>
      <li><strong>AI Camera</strong>Machine vision module — kids train it themselves to recognize colors, objects, and obstacles</li>
      <li><strong>Chassis</strong>Custom-designed frame — assembled by hand during camp, no glue, all screws and snap-fits</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="section-title">Built over 5 days</h2>
    <p class="rover-text">Each day of Mission Mars adds a new capability to the rover. Day 1: chassis and motors. Day 2: the gripper. Day 3: the drill. Day 4: the AI camera. Day 5: the full autonomous mission — plant life on Mars.</p>
    <p class="rover-text">Every child builds their own rover from components. No two are identical. By the end of the week, they've assembled a working robot that can drive, grip, drill, see, and act on its own.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h3>Your child takes it home</h3>
      <p>The rover — including all electronics, motors, camera, and the Arduino board — belongs to your child. They can keep programming it, modifying it, and building new missions at home.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="section-title">No experience needed</h2>
    <p class="rover-text">All soldering, wiring, and tricky prep work is done before camp by our engineer. Children work with safe, pre-prepared components — they get the exciting parts: building, programming, and commanding their rover.</p>
    <p class="rover-text">Programming is done with colorful blocks and icons — no reading or typing required. If your child can stack LEGO, they can build and program this rover.</p>

    <div style="text-align:center; margin: 40px 0;">
